{"title_page": "Jan Vercruysse", "text_new": "\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jan Vercruysse\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1948|10|03}}\n| birth_place        = [[Ostend]], [[Belgium]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2018|02|27|1948|10|03}}\n| death_place        = [[Bruges]], [[Belgium]]\n| resting_place      = \n| nationality        = {{plainlist|\n* Belgian\n* Dutch<ref name=\":3\" />\n}}\n| residence          = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = Artist\n| years_active       = 1974 - 2018\n| net_worth          = \n| title              = \n| boards             = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| parents            = {{ubl|Ir\u00e8ne De Ketelaere|Pierre Marie Joseph Vercruysse}}<ref name=\":2\" />\n| website            = \n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n}}\n\n'''Jan Vercruysse''' (3 October 1948<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.tillo.be/p603.htm|title=Persoonsblad|last=Behaeghe|first=Tillo|date=13 August 2018|website=Tillo Behaeghe|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180311021100/http://tillo.be/p603.htm|archive-date=11 March 2018|url-status=live|access-date=13 August 2018}}</ref> - 27 February 2018<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://nl.metrotime.be/2018/03/03/news/beeldend-kunstenaar-jan-vercruysse-overleden|title=Beeldend kunstenaar Jan Vercruysse overleden|date=3 March 2018|website=Metro|language=Dutch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427081119/http://nl.metrotime.be/2018/03/03/news/beeldend-kunstenaar-jan-vercruysse-overleden|archive-date=27 April 2018|url-status=live|access-date=13 August 2018}}</ref>) was a [[Belgians|Belgian]] contemporary visual artist, sculptor and photographer.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://vocab.getty.edu/page/ulan/500101096|title=Union List of Artist Names|website=The Getty|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529045210/http://getty.edu/vow/ULANFullDisplay?find=&role=&nation=&subjectid=500101096|archive-date=29 May 2016|access-date=13 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Life and work==\nVercruysse was born in [[Ostend]] and died in [[Bruges]], both [[Flemish Region|Flemish]] municipalities in [[Belgium]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://xavierhufkens.com/artists/jan-vercruysse|title=Jan Vercruysse|date=19 June 2018|website=Xavier Hufkens|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180202231147/http://xavierhufkens.com/artists/jan-vercruysse|archive-date=2 February 2018|access-date=13 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Prior to becoming a visual artist and photographer in 1974, Vercruysse studied law and had been a poet.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs a sculptor, his work featured [[Found object|industrial materials]] such as [[Weathering steel|corten steel]], [[bronze]], [[iron]] and [[glass]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artsy.net/artist/jan-vercruysse|title=Jon Vercruysse|date=13 August 2018|website=Artsy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619113351/http://artsy.net/artist/jan-vercruysse|archive-date=19 June 2018|access-date=13 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe has also previously lived and worked in [[Italy]] and [[Spain]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tate.org.uk/art/artworks/vercruysse-m-m10-t11944|title=\u2018M(M10)\u2019, Jan Vercruysse, 1993|last=Mundy|first=Jennifer|date=January 2005|website=Tate|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714023254/http://tate.org.uk/art/artworks/vercruysse-m-m10-t11944|archive-date=14 July 2018|access-date=13 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Vercruysse represented his country [[Belgium]] at the [[Venice Biennale]] in 1993, where he exhibited a selection of his work.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nVercruysse's work is part of many important [[Europe|European]] and [[North America|American]] museum collections and is referred to as one of Belgium's most influential artists.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mleuven.be/en/jan-vercruysse|title=Jan Vercruysse|date=13 August 2018|website=M - Museum Leuven|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180812180116/https://www.mleuven.be/en/jan-vercruysse|archive-date=12 August 2018|access-date=13 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://artlead.net/artists-vercruysse-jan|title=Jan Vercruysse|date=13 August 2018|website=artlead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180812175001/http://artlead.net/artists-vercruysse-jan|archive-date=12 August 2018|access-date=13 August 2018}}</ref>Today, he is represented by [[Xavier Hufkens]] Gallery in Brussels and Vistamare and Tucci Russo in Italy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://xavierhufkens.com/artists/jan-vercruysse|title=Jan Vercruysse Artist Page|last=|first=|date=|website=Xavier Hufkens|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuccirusso.com/index.php?PHPSESSID=vrv77psl2kgbmufbguucqbehg2|title=Artist page|last=|first=|date=|website=Tucci Russo|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vistamare.com/en/artisti/jan-vercruysse/opere/|title=Artist Page|last=|first=|date=|website=Vistamare|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\nFlemish Culture Prize for the Visual Arts (2001)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Museum exhibitions==\nA selection of exhibitions of work produced by Jan include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://xavierhufkens.com/artists/jan-vercruysse/download/artist-file-verc-bio.pdf|title=Jan Vercruysse (Biography)|date=19 June 2018|website=Xavier Hufkens|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315133449/http://xavierhufkens.com/artists/jan-vercruysse/download/artist-file-verc-bio.pdf|archive-date=15 March 2018|access-date=13 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*''Works 1975-2009'', [[M - Museum Leuven]], Belgium (2009)\n*''Salto Prolungato'', Museum Dhondt-Dhaenens, Deurle, Belgium (2001)\n*''Portretten van de Kunstenaar \u2013 Portraits de l\u2019Artiste'', [[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels|Centre for Fine Arts]], Brussels, Belgium (1999)\n*''Portretten van de Kunstenaar \u2013 Portraits of the Artist'', [[Van Abbemuseum]], Eindhoven, Netherlands (1998)\n*''The Villas, Haus Lange \u2013 Haus Esters'', Krefelder Museen, Krefeld, Germany (1995)\n*[[The Power Plant]], Toronto, Ontario, Canada (1993)\n* Padiglione di Belgio, [[Venice Biennale]], Venice, Italy (1993)\n*''Tombeaux'', Museo d\u2019Arte Contemporanea, [[Castle of Rivoli]], Rivoli, Italy (1992)\n*[[Van Abbemuseum]], Eindhoven, Netherlands (1992)\n*[[Kunsthalle Bern]], Bern, Switzerland (1989)\n*[[Palais des Beaux-Arts de Lille]], Brussels, Belgium (1988)\n* ARC, [[Mus\u00e9e d'Art Moderne de la Ville de Paris|City of Paris Museum of Modern Art]], Paris, France (1986)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://janvercruyssefoundation.com Official Website]\n*[http://www.xavierhufkens.com/artists/jan-vercruysse Jan Vercruysse] at [[Xavier Hufkens]], Brussels, Belgium\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vercruysse, Jan}}\n[[Category:People from Ostend]]\n[[Category:Belgian contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n\n\n\n\n{{Belgium-artist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jan Vercruysse\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1948|10|03}}\n| birth_place        = [[Ostend]], [[Belgium]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2018|02|27|1948|10|03}}\n| death_place        = [[Bruges]], [[Belgium]]\n| resting_place      = \n| nationality        = {{plainlist|\n* Belgian\n* Dutch<ref name=\":3\" />\n}}\n| residence          = \n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = Artist\n| years_active       = 1974 - 2018\n| net_worth          = \n| title              = \n| boards             = \n| spouse             = \n| children           = \n| parents            = {{ubl|Ir\u00e8ne De Ketelaere|Pierre Marie Joseph Vercruysse}}<ref name=\":2\" />\n| website            = \n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n}}\n\n'''Jan Vercruysse''' (3 October 1948<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.tillo.be/p603.htm|title=Persoonsblad|last=Behaeghe|first=Tillo|date=13 August 2018|website=Tillo Behaeghe|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180311021100/http://tillo.be/p603.htm|archive-date=11 March 2018|url-status=live|access-date=13 August 2018}}</ref> - 27 February 2018<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://nl.metrotime.be/2018/03/03/news/beeldend-kunstenaar-jan-vercruysse-overleden|title=Beeldend kunstenaar Jan Vercruysse overleden|date=3 March 2018|website=Metro|language=Dutch|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180427081119/http://nl.metrotime.be/2018/03/03/news/beeldend-kunstenaar-jan-vercruysse-overleden|archive-date=27 April 2018|url-status=live|access-date=13 August 2018}}</ref>) was a [[Belgians|Belgian]] contemporary visual artist, sculptor and photographer.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://vocab.getty.edu/page/ulan/500101096|title=Union List of Artist Names|website=The Getty|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529045210/http://getty.edu/vow/ULANFullDisplay?find=&role=&nation=&subjectid=500101096|archive-date=29 May 2016|access-date=13 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Life and work==\nVercruysse was born in [[Ostend]] and died in [[Bruges]], both [[Flemish Region|Flemish]] municipalities in [[Belgium]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://xavierhufkens.com/artists/jan-vercruysse|title=Jan Vercruysse|date=19 June 2018|website=Xavier Hufkens|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180202231147/http://xavierhufkens.com/artists/jan-vercruysse|archive-date=2 February 2018|access-date=13 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Prior to becoming a visual artist and photographer in 1974, Vercruysse studied law and had been a poet.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs a sculptor, his work featured [[Found object|industrial materials]] such as [[Weathering steel|corten steel]], [[bronze]], [[iron]] and [[glass]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artsy.net/artist/jan-vercruysse|title=Jon Vercruysse|date=13 August 2018|website=Artsy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180619113351/http://artsy.net/artist/jan-vercruysse|archive-date=19 June 2018|access-date=13 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe has also previously lived and worked in [[Italy]] and [[Spain]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tate.org.uk/art/artworks/vercruysse-m-m10-t11944|title=\u2018M(M10)\u2019, Jan Vercruysse, 1993|last=Mundy|first=Jennifer|date=January 2005|website=Tate|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714023254/http://tate.org.uk/art/artworks/vercruysse-m-m10-t11944|archive-date=14 July 2018|access-date=13 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Vercruysse represented his country [[Belgium]] at the [[Venice Biennale]] in 1993, where he exhibited a selection of his work.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nVercruysse's work is part of many important [[Europe|European]] and [[North America|American]] museum collections and is referred to as one of Belgium's most influential artists.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mleuven.be/en/jan-vercruysse|title=Jan Vercruysse|date=13 August 2018|website=M - Museum Leuven|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180812180116/https://www.mleuven.be/en/jan-vercruysse|archive-date=12 August 2018|access-date=13 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://artlead.net/artists-vercruysse-jan|title=Jan Vercruysse|date=13 August 2018|website=artlead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180812175001/http://artlead.net/artists-vercruysse-jan|archive-date=12 August 2018|access-date=13 August 2018}}</ref>Today, he is represented by [[Xavier Hufkens]] Gallery in Brussels and Vistamare and Tutti Rucco in Italy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://xavierhufkens.com/artists/jan-vercruysse|title=Artist page|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tuccirusso.com/index.php?PHPSESSID=vrv77psl2kgbmufbguucqbehg2|title=Artist page|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.vistamare.com/en/artisti/jan-vercruysse/opere/|title=Artist Page|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 April, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\nFlemish Culture Prize for the Visual Arts (2001)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Museum exhibitions==\nA selection of exhibitions of work produced by Jan include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://xavierhufkens.com/artists/jan-vercruysse/download/artist-file-verc-bio.pdf|title=Jan Vercruysse (Biography)|date=19 June 2018|website=Xavier Hufkens|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180315133449/http://xavierhufkens.com/artists/jan-vercruysse/download/artist-file-verc-bio.pdf|archive-date=15 March 2018|access-date=13 August 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n*''Works 1975-2009'', [[M - Museum Leuven]], Belgium (2009)\n*''Salto Prolungato'', Museum Dhondt-Dhaenens, Deurle, Belgium (2001)\n*''Portretten van de Kunstenaar \u2013 Portraits de l\u2019Artiste'', [[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels|Centre for Fine Arts]], Brussels, Belgium (1999)\n*''Portretten van de Kunstenaar \u2013 Portraits of the Artist'', [[Van Abbemuseum]], Eindhoven, Netherlands (1998)\n*''The Villas, Haus Lange \u2013 Haus Esters'', Krefelder Museen, Krefeld, Germany (1995)\n*[[The Power Plant]], Toronto, Ontario, Canada (1993)\n* Padiglione di Belgio, [[Venice Biennale]], Venice, Italy (1993)\n*''Tombeaux'', Museo d\u2019Arte Contemporanea, [[Castle of Rivoli]], Rivoli, Italy (1992)\n*[[Van Abbemuseum]], Eindhoven, Netherlands (1992)\n*[[Kunsthalle Bern]], Bern, Switzerland (1989)\n*[[Palais des Beaux-Arts de Lille]], Brussels, Belgium (1988)\n* ARC, [[Mus\u00e9e d'Art Moderne de la Ville de Paris|City of Paris Museum of Modern Art]], Paris, France (1986)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://janvercruyssefoundation.com Official Website]\n*[http://www.xavierhufkens.com/artists/jan-vercruysse Jan Vercruysse] at [[Xavier Hufkens]], Brussels, Belgium\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vercruysse, Jan}}\n[[Category:People from Ostend]]\n[[Category:Belgian contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n\n\n\n\n{{Belgium-artist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Madehp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife and work", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jan_Vercruysse"}
{"title_page": "Moppin Complex", "text_new": "{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = Moppin Complex\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| type           = [[Complex (geology)|Complex]]\n| age            =  [[Statherian]]\n| prilithology   = [[Metavolcanic rock]]\n| otherlithology = [[Metasedimentary rock]]\n| namedfor       = Moppin Ranch<ref name=\"barker1958\">{{cite journal |last1=Barker |first1=Fred |title=Precambrian and Tertiary geology of Las Tablas quadrangle, New Mexico |journal=New Mexico Bureau of Mines and Mineral Resources Bulletin |date=1958 |volume=45 |url=https://geoinfo.nmt.edu/publications/monographs/bulletins/downloads/45/Bulletin45.pdf}}</ref>\n| namedby        = F. Barker (1958)\n| region         = [[Tusas Mountains]], [[New Mexico]]\n| country        = [[United States]]\n| coordinates    = {{Coord|36.675|N|106.208|W}}\n| unitof         =\n| subunits       =\n| underlies      = [[Vadito Group]]\n| overlies       = \n| thickness      =\n| extent         =\n| area           =\n| map            =\n| map_caption    =\n}}\n\nThe '''Moppin Complex''' is a [[Precambrian]] [[Complex (geology)|geologic complex]] in [[New Mexico]]. It crops out in the [[Tusas Mountains]] along a belt from American Creek ({{Coord|36.630|N|106.072|W}}) to Jawbone Mountain ({{Coord|36.743|N|106.244|W}}). It is one of the oldest known rock units in New Mexico,<ref name=\"mclemore2011\">{{cite journal |last1=McLemore |first1=Virginia T. |title=Geology and mineral resources in the Hopewell and Bromide No. 2 districts, northern Tusas Mountains, Rio Arriba County, New Mexico |journal=New Mexico Geological Society Field Conference Series |date=2011 |volume=62 |pages=379\u2013388 |url=https://nmgs.nmt.edu/publications/guidebooks/downloads/62/62_p0379_p0388.pdf}}</ref> with a minimum [[Radiometric dating|radiometric age]] of 1.755 [[Billion years | Gya]], and likely correlates with the Pecos Complex of the [[Sangre de Cristo Mountains|Santa Fe Mountains]] and the Gold Hill Complex of the [[Sangre de Cristo Mountains|Taos Mountains]]<ref name=\"bw1989\">{{cite journal |last1=Bauer |first1=Paul W. |last2=Williams |first2=Michael L. |title=Stratigraphic nomenclature ol proterozoic rocks, northern New Mexico-revisions, redefinitions, and formaliza |journal=New Mexico Geology |date=August 1989 |volume=11 |issue=3 |url=https://geoinfo.nmt.edu/publications/periodicals/nmg/11/n3/nmg_v11_n3_p45.pdf |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe rock beds making up the Moppin Complex were originally named the Hopewell Series in 1937,<ref name=\"just1937\">{{cite journal |last1=Just |first1=Evan |title=Geology and economic features of the pegmatites of Taos and Rio Arriba Counties, New Mexico: New Mexico School of Mines Bulletin |journal=New Mexico School of Mines Bulletin |date=1937 |issue=13}}</ref>, but this name was already in use and the unit was renamed the Moppin metavolcanic series in 1958.<ref name=\"barker1958\"/> With the recognition that the lithology was more diverse, the unit was renamed as the Moppin Complex in 1989.<ref name=\"bw1989\"/>\n\nThe unit is at least several thousand feet thick<ref name=\"barker1958\"/> and consists mostly of [[chlorite]] [[shist]] and [[amphibolite]], but with lesser amounts of many other rock types, including feldspathic schist, [[muscovite]] schist, metaconglomerate, and [[banded iron formation]]. [[Pillow lavas]] can be discerned at some locations. It is intruded by plutonic rocks, including the Maquinita Granodiorite and the [[trondjhemite]] of Rio Brazos. The Maquinita Granodiorite has a [[Uranium-lead dating|uranium-lead]] radiometric age of 1.755 Gya, which constrains the minimum age of the Moppin Complex.<ref name=\"bw1989\"/>\n\nThe unit is interpreted as a portion of a juvenile island arc accreted to the southern margin of [[Laurentia]] as part of the Yavapai Province between 1.8 and 1.755 Gya. The unit was intruded by the Tres Piedras Metagranite between 1.700 and 1.693 Gya as part of the transition to the Mazazatl orogeny, and further deformed between 1.45 and 1.35 Gya.<ref name=\"dwk2011\">{{cite journal |last1=Davis |first1=Peter |last2=Williams |first2=Mike |last3=Karlstrom |first3=Karl |title=Structural evolution and timing of deformation along the Proterozoic Spring Creek shear zone of the northern Tusas Mountains, New Mexico |journal=New Mexico Geological Society Field Conference Series |date=2011 |volume=62 |pages=177\u2013190 |url=https://nmgs.nmt.edu/publications/guidebooks/downloads/62/62_p0177_p0190.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"daa2016\">{{cite journal |last1=Damiel |first1=Christopher G. |last2=Andronicos |first2=Christopher L. |last3=Aronoff |first3=Ruth F. |title=Regional Al2SiO5 triple-point metamorphic rocks of northern New Mexico; A field trip to honor the career contributions od Lincoln Hollister to petrology and tectonics |journal=The Geological Society of America Field Guide Series |date=2016 |volume=44 |pages=201\u2013229}}</ref>\n\nGold has been mined in the Moppin Complex and comes from volcanogenic massive-sulfide deposits. Banded iron formation may amount to 100 million tons of low-grade iron ore, but this is not presently economically recoverable.<ref name=\"mclemore2011\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Precambrian geology of New Mexico]]\n\n{{NewMexico-geologic-formation-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = Moppin Complex\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| type           = [[Complex (geology)|Complex]]\n| age            =  [[Statherian]]\n| prilithology   = [[Metavolcanic rock]]\n| otherlithology = [[Metasedimentary rock]]\n| namedfor       = Moppin Ranch<ref name=\"barker1958\">{{cite journal |last1=Barker |first1=Fred |title=Precambrian and Tertiary geology of Las Tablas quadrangle, New Mexico |journal=New Mexico Bureau of Mines and Mineral Resources Bulletin |date=1958 |volume=45 |url=https://geoinfo.nmt.edu/publications/monographs/bulletins/downloads/45/Bulletin45.pdf}}</ref>\n| namedby        = F. Barker (1958)\n| region         = [[Tusas Mountains]], [[New Mexico]]\n| country        = [[United States]]\n| coordinates    = {{Coord|36.675|N|106.208|W}}\n| unitof         =\n| subunits       =\n| underlies      = [[Vadito Group]]\n| overlies       = \n| thickness      =\n| extent         =\n| area           =\n| map            =\n| map_caption    =\n}}\n\nThe '''Moppin Complex''' is a [[Precambrian]] [[Complex (geology)|geologic complex]] in [[New Mexico]]. It crops out in the [[Tusas Mountains]] along a belt from American Creek ({{Coord|36.630|N|106.072|W}}) to Jawbone Mountain ({{Coord|36.743|N|106.244|W}}). It is one of the oldest known rock units in New Mexico,<ref name=\"mclemore2011\">{{cite journal |last1=McLemore |first1=Virginia T. |title=Geology and mineral resources in the Hopewell and Bromide No. 2 districts, northern Tusas Mountains, Rio Arriba County, New Mexico |journal=New Mexico Geological Society Field Conference Series |date=2011 |volume=62 |pages=379\u2013388 |url=https://nmgs.nmt.edu/publications/guidebooks/downloads/62/62_p0379_p0388.pdf}}</ref> with a minimum [[Radiometric dating|radiometric age]] 1.755 [[Billion years | Gya]], and likely correlates with the Pecos Complex of the [[Sangre de Cristo Mountains|Santa Fe Mountains]] and the Gold Hill Complex of the [[Sangre de Cristo Mountains|Taos Mountains]]<ref name=\"bw1989\">{{cite journal |last1=Bauer |first1=Paul W. |last2=Williams |first2=Michael L. |title=Stratigraphic nomenclature ol proterozoic rocks, northern New Mexico-revisions, redefinitions, and formaliza |journal=New Mexico Geology |date=August 1989 |volume=11 |issue=3 |url=https://geoinfo.nmt.edu/publications/periodicals/nmg/11/n3/nmg_v11_n3_p45.pdf |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe rock beds making up the Moppin Complex were originally named the Hopewell Series in 1937,<ref name=\"just1937\">{{cite journal |last1=Just |first1=Evan |title=Geology and economic features of the pegmatites of Taos and Rio Arriba Counties, New Mexico: New Mexico School of Mines Bulletin |journal=New Mexico School of Mines Bulletin |date=1937 |issue=13}}</ref>, but this name was already in use and the unit was renamed the Moppin metavolcanic series in 1958.<ref name=\"barker1958\"/> With the recognition that the lithology was more diverse, the unit was renamed as the Moppin Complex in 1989.<ref name=\"bw1989\"/>\n\nThe unit is at least several thousand feet thick<ref name=\"barker1958\"/> and consists mostly of [[chlorite]] [[shist]] and [[amphibolite]], but with lesser amounts of many other rock types, including feldspathic schist, [[muscovite]] schist, metaconglomerate, and [[banded iron formation]]. [[Pillow lavas]] can be discerned at some locations. It is intruded by plutonic rocks, including the Maquinita Granodiorite and the [[trondjhemite]] of Rio Brazos. The Maquinita Granodiorite has a [[Uranium-lead dating|uranium-lead]] radiometric age of 1.755 Gya, which constrains the minimum age of the Moppin Complex.<ref name=\"bw1989\"/>\n\nThe unit is interpreted as a portion of a juvenile island arc accreted to the southern margin of [[Laurentia]] as part of the Yavapai Province between 1.8 and 1.755 Gya. The unit was intruded by the Tres Piedras Metagranite between 1.700 and 1.693 Gya as part of the transition to the Mazazatl orogeny, and further deformed between 1.45 and 1.35 Gya.<ref name=\"dwk2011\">{{cite journal |last1=Davis |first1=Peter |last2=Williams |first2=Mike |last3=Karlstrom |first3=Karl |title=Structural evolution and timing of deformation along the Proterozoic Spring Creek shear zone of the northern Tusas Mountains, New Mexico |journal=New Mexico Geological Society Field Conference Series |date=2011 |volume=62 |pages=177\u2013190 |url=https://nmgs.nmt.edu/publications/guidebooks/downloads/62/62_p0177_p0190.pdf}}</ref><ref name=\"daa2016\">{{cite journal |last1=Damiel |first1=Christopher G. |last2=Andronicos |first2=Christopher L. |last3=Aronoff |first3=Ruth F. |title=Regional Al2SiO5 triple-point metamorphic rocks of northern New Mexico; A field trip to honor the career contributions od Lincoln Hollister to petrology and tectonics |journal=The Geological Society of America Field Guide Series |date=2016 |volume=44 |pages=201\u2013229}}</ref>\n\nGold has been mined in the Moppin Complex and comes from volcanogenic massive-sulfide deposits. Banded iron formation may amount to 100 million tons of low-grade iron ore, but this is not presently economically recoverable.<ref name=\"mclemore2011\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Precambrian geology of New Mexico]]\n\n{{NewMexico-geologic-formation-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kent G. Budge", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moppin_Complex"}
{"title_page": "4 O'Clock Club", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = 4 O'Clock Club\n| image                    = 4 O'Clock Club titlecard.png\n| caption                  = \n| runtime                  = 27\u201328 minutes\n| genre                    = [[Children's television series|Children's drama]]<br>[[Musical comedy]]<br>[[Family sitcom]]\n| creator                  = [[Paul Rose (writer)|Paul Rose]]<br>[[Doc Brown (rapper)|Doc Brown]]\n| executive_producer       = Connal Orton\n| starring                 = Various\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| network                  = [[CBBC (TV channel)|CBBC]] (2012\u2013present)<br />[[CBBC HD]] (2013\u2013present)\n| first_aired              = 13 January 2012 \u2013 present\n| num_series               = 9\n| num_episodes             = 114\n| list_episodes            = List of 4 O'Clock Club episodes\n}}\n'''''4 O'Clock Club''''' is a British comedy drama<ref>https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/4_oclock_club/</ref> and musical [[children's television series]] set in a secondary school, which premiered on 13 January 2012<ref name=s1s1>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/b019h55d/4_oClock_Club_Back_to_School/|title=BBC iPlayer \u2013 4 o'Clock Club: Back To School}}</ref> on [[CBBC (TV channel)|CBBC]] and [[CBBC HD]]. A second series began airing on 4 January 2013, and the third series premiered on 20 December 2013.<ref>[http://screenterrier.blogspot.co.uk/2014/01/cbbc-casting-for-4-oclock-club.html CBBC Casting for 4 O'Clock Club] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202120143/http://screenterrier.blogspot.co.uk/2014/01/cbbc-casting-for-4-oclock-club.html |date=2 February 2014 }} (28 January 2014) ''ScreenTerrier''. Retrieved 31 January 2014</ref> Series 4 began airing on 28 January 2015, and Series 5 was aired on CBBC and CBBC HD from February to May 2016.\n\nThe show's seventh series started airing from 24 January 2018, and ended on 18 April 2018. Series 8 began on CBBC with a Christmas special on 19 December 2018, and continued airing on CBBC from 6 February 2019, and ended on 17 April 2019.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/schedules/p00fzl9r/2019/02/06</ref> Series 9 began airing on 4 February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/4_oclock_club/episodes/9/1/|title=4 O'Clock Club Series 9, Episode 1 - AXOLOTL|last=Guide|first=British Comedy|website=British Comedy Guide|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nIn March 2011, auditions were held for ''4 O'Clock Club'', and the show was publicly announced the next month.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2011/04_april/21/cbbc.shtml \"CBBC announces in. house drama line-up\"]. ''BBC Press Office'' (21 April 2011). Retrieved 31 January 2014</ref> In January 2012, the first episode aired, with the series wrapping up in March of the same year.\n\n==Synopsis==\n{{Main|List of 4 O'Clock Club episodes}}\n\n===Series 1 (2012)===\nThe first series centres on Josh Carter ([[Khalil Madovi]]), a pupil at Elmsbury High, and his older brother Nathan ([[Doc Brown (rapper)|Doc Brown]]), who works as a teacher there. Josh is portrayed as a laid back teenage schoolboy trying to maintain his cool reputation, while also being rebellious and trying to cause trouble in order to achieve his goals and humiliate or outsmart Nathan. Nathan, former Elmsbury High student and famous rapper, soon learns that only he will able to stop Josh from his schemes.\n\n===Series 2 (2013)===\nIn the second series, Nathan leaves Elmsbury and new music teacher Dexter Harris (Jason Callender) joins the school. Dexter becomes Josh and his mother's new lodger, taking Josh's room as a result. As such, Josh antagonizes Dexter through much of the series, until he finally accepts his presence and labels him as an \"honorary Carter brother\". The series also featured Crispin Bell ([[Simon Lowe]]) as the new headmaster, who replaces Byron, and proved to be far stricter than Byron. Mr Bell was a brutal enemy of Josh and Dexter for the remainder of the series. Issac (Layton Blake) made a guest and a 1st appearance in Series 2 Episode 1 but his name wasn't confirmed and the credits says \"Fowlmere Josh\".\n\n===Series 3 (2013\u201314)===\nThe third series featured Nathan's proposal and marriage to Melanie Poppy ([[Laura Aikman]]), who both departed the series, and Josh is forced to share his room with his annoying younger cousin, Nero ([[Akai Osei]]). When the school burns down due to an issue with candles, Elmsbury is merged with another school, Fowlmere Manor, renaming the school Elmsmere Manor High as of the fourth episode of the third series. Molly and Ryan do not appear in the rest of the series, and attend a new school off screen. \n\nDue to the merger, several new characters joined the series in episode three, these were PE teacher Mr Nunn ([[Dan Wright (comedian)|Dan Wright]]), Miss Parkwood ([[Sophia Di Martino]]) and pupils in Nero's year; Eli Grant (Daniel Kerr), Owen Garland (Lewis Brindley), Fleur Murphy (Chloe Davison) and Eleesha Rahad (Grace McIntosh). [[Sally Ann Matthews]] also joined the cast as head teacher Aine O'Brien and a pupil in Josh's year: Issac Rodgers (Layton Blake) who is now a main character.\n\n===Series 4 (2015)===\nThe fourth series features Nero, now in the main role, and his crew have replaced Josh and the Elmsbury gang who have all temporarily departed the series (except Isaac, who becomes Elmsmere's caretaker) and Dexter is trying to make it as an accomplished teacher, but is given the new job of taking care of Nero's shenanigans, which indirectly resembles Josh and Nathan's relationship in the first series. The teachers who appeared in Series 3, Miss Parkwood and Aine O'Brien do not appear in this series, leading to the re introduction of former head teacher Anita Andress (Liz Hume-Dawson). \n\nThe series also introduced a new main character, rebellious and cynical tomboy Clem Burton ([[Jade Alleyne]]), who joins Nero's crew as well as mysterious spray paintings of Andress appear around Elmsmere, called 'The Phantom Sprayer', however it was later revealed that it was Mr. Bell who was the criminal. A new love interest for Dexter, Science teacher Lizzie Baker (Sarah Schoenbeck), is introduced in episode one. \n\nA new recurring character, Isobel Harlow ([[Ruby Barnhill]]) appears from episode three. This series also features mini cameos from Josh's gang as shown in the series premiere and series finale. Nathan also makes his comeback in two episodes and is now a father to baby Moses.\n\n===Series 5 (2016)===\nIn the fifth series, all the characters from the fourth series remain apart from Miss Andress. , but with three new characters, Lizzie's younger sister Amber (Ella Marshall Pinder) and her friends Violet (Cara Jenkins) and Darnesh (Riley McCormick) who want to fit in with the \"cool\" kids, like Nero and his gang. Zoe-Marie's younger sister Ingrid (Zara Thurstan) also starts at the school and quickly becomes Amber's enemy. A new head teacher is also introduced in the first episode, Mrs Helena Goodman ([[Victoria Carling]]). \n\nThroughout the series, both Nero and Clem try to tell each other how they feel about each other. Dexter and Lizzie are dating but must hide it from others, though Mr Nunn ([[Dan Wright (comedian)|Dan Wright]]) tries to hit on Lizzie. Amber, and her gang try to beat their bully Ingrid and Dexter and Nero face problems living together.\n\n===Series 6 (2017)===\nIn the sixth series, Nero and Clem have finally begun dating after their summer romance, but eventually break up after their several arguments. Clem departs in episode three to pursue a career in music. Dexter and Lizzie are expecting a baby, and eventually give birth to twins named Albert and Faraday. After his divorce in the previous series, and a brief relationship with newcomer Anastasia (Rachel Elizabeth Kelly), Bell finds himself living in a run down caravan on the school grounds with his estranged son CJ (Rufus King-Dabbs), a newcomer to the series. \n\nDexter and Nero are both shocked at CJ's arrival, as Bell never mentioned in any previous series that he had a child. The series also introduces the characters of Polly Morgan (Mischa Eckersley), a fellow pupil of Nero's whom he tries to impress throughout the series and Owen's younger brother Chester (Rohan Green). In Series 6, Isobel Harlow was promoted to a series regular as she appeared in every episode.\n\n===Series 7 (2018)===\nThe seventh series started airing on 24 January 2018. All the main characters from the previous series returned apart from Isobel Harlow ([[Ruby Barnhill]]). Elmsmere School has moved to a new location after debt caused the old school to be closed. Mr. Bell becomes stand in headteacher, while Helena Goodman takes time off to reflect on the financial issues of the old site. She returns for the final four episodes of the season. Nero's character departs in the fourth episode to pursue new experiences in America along with Dexter and Lizzie. 3 new characters were introduced also in the 4th episode: Science teacher Maddie Harper ([[Genesis Lynea]]), her son Jack Harper (Ashton Henry-Reid) and Music teacher Danny Boyd (Nathan Clarke).\n\n===Series 8 (2018\u201319)===\nThe eighth series began with a special for Christmas on 19 December 2018, focusing on Mr Bell and his relationship with son CJ. The rest of the series began on [[CBBC]] on 6 February 2019, and was on the [[BBC iPlayer]] every Wednesday from 5:00 pm. <ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/schedules/p00fzl9r/2019/02/06</ref> Evan (Zak Sutcliffe) was introduced in this series as a 6th former student who is also a rebel. Nero returns as a guest on the 100th episode special which was the 9th Episode is the 8th Series. All the cast from the previous series return, with Mrs Goodman (Victoria Carling) leaving in episode four.\n\n===Series 9 (2020)===\nThe ninth series began airing on 4 February 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/tv/4_oclock_club/episodes/9/1/|title=4 O'Clock Club Series 9, Episode 1 - AXOLOTL|last=Guide|first=British Comedy|website=British Comedy Guide|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> This series saw a mini-reboot. PC Emily Rowe ([[Leah Hackett]]) who has appeared since the second series becomes a series regular. New characters Coco (Carys John) and Reiss (Aled Arhyel) were introduced as PC Rowe's niece and nephew, and are put into the care of Rowe after their mother is arrested. They are joined by new classmates Henry (Finley Allgrove) and Magnus (Harley Harrison). New music teacher Clinton Russell (Andy Umerah) was introduced as well, who replaces Danny, and he also dates PC Rowe. \n\nAll the cast return from the previous series, with the exception of Maddie and Jack Harper (Genesis Lynea and Ashton Henry-Reid), Eli Grant (Daniel Kerr) and Mr Danny Boyd (Nathan Clarke) who all have left the series off screen. Episode three sees new member of staff Miss Wrigley (Holly Freeman) join the series. Episode five saw  Mr Nunn (Dan Wright) learn that new pupil Henry is his son.\n\nThe end of the series will see the remainder of Nero's gang leave Elmsmere.\n\n==Cast==\n\n===Main characters===\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n\n! style=\"width:140px;\"| Character\n! style=\"width:140px;\"| Actor/actress\n! style=\"width:140px;\"| Role\n! style=\"width:150px;\"| Duration\n! style=\"width:140px;\"| Year(s)\n|-\n| Mr Crispin Bell || [[Simon Lowe]] || Headteacher (2x01\u20133x02, 8x04-), <br>Co Headteacher (3x03\u20133x13), <br>History Teacher (4x01\u2013), <br>Deputy Headteacher (5x01\u20137x02), <br>Acting  Headteacher (7x02\u20138x04) || 2x01\u2013 || 2013\u2013\n|-\n| PC Emily Rowe || Leah Hackett || Police Officer <br> Reiss and Coco's Auntie || 2x04\u2013 || 2013\u2013\n|-\n| Isaac Rodgers || Layton Blake ||Student (3x03-3x13), <br>Caretaker (4x01\