{"title_page": "Georgina Callaghan", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2009}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image               = Callaghan 5 24 2014 -10 (14270528514).jpg\n| name                = Georgina Callaghan\n| caption             = \n| image_size          =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_date          = \n| origin              = [[Grantham, Lincolnshire]], England\n| instrument          = singing, acoustic guitar, piano\n| genre               = Pop singer-songwriter\n| occupation          = Singer-songwriter\n| years_active        = 2005\u2013present\n| label               = Green Town Music\n| associated_acts = [[Shawn Mullins]]\n| website             = {{url|https://callaghansongs.com}}\n}}\n\nBritish artist Callaghan (full name Georgina Callaghan) is a singer-songwriter. She performs under the name Callaghan. She is best known for her 2012 album \"Life in Full Colour\" produced by Grammy-nominated US artist Shawn Mullins.\n\nCallaghan is currently living in Los Angeles where she is recording her 3rd studio album.\n\n== Biography ==\nCallaghan wrote her first song at the age of 14 and earned a place on [[BBC]] TV show ''Get Your Act Together'',<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0187641   The Internet Movie Database Page]</ref> hosted by Irish singer [[Ronan Keating]].\n\nCallaghan has worked with many musicians and producers including Grammy Award-winning writer John Peppard (1998, [[Grammy Award for Best Country Collaboration with Vocals|Best Country Collaboration with Vocals]] for \"[[In Another's Eyes]]\") and producer Peter Lawlor who formed the band [[Stiltskin]].<ref>[http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=Garth+Brooks&title=&year=1997&genre=8   1998 Grammy Award Database]</ref><ref>[http://www.amug.org/~scrnsrc/grammys_98.html Screen Source presents The 40th Annual Grammy Awards| Screen Source presents The 40th Annual Grammy Awards] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017114952/http://www.amug.org/~scrnsrc/grammys_98.html |date=17 October 2007 }}</ref> \n[[Image:Callaghannationaltheatre.JPG|thumb|320px|left|Callaghan performing at The National Theatre London 2009]]\n\nIn 2008, Callaghan self-released single \"Look Around\". Doing all of the PR and radio plugging herself, Callaghan achieved airplay on numerous [[BBC]] radio stations, extensive local and national press coverage as well as a performance on [[British Sky Broadcasting|Sky TV]].<ref>[http://www.metro.co.uk/fame/article.html?Georgina_Callaghan_takes_on_X_Factor&in_article_id=355894&in_page_id=7 Metro.co.uk]</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=48im-bdo1aI Callaghan performs Look Around on Sky TV]</ref> All proceeds from the sale of the single went to music charity Live Music Now.<ref>[http://www.prsformusic.com/creators/news/news/Pages/Callaghan.aspx PRS Web site]</ref>\n\nIn July 2009, Callaghan travelled to [[Georgia, USA]] to record with US artist [[Shawn Mullins]]. The first single from the collaboration \"Smile\" was played and endorsed on the [[Bob Harris (radio)|Bob Harris]] Country Show on [[BBC Radio 2]].<ref>[http://www.bobharris.org/pages/playlist.asp?progcode=c13082009 Bob Harris Country Show Playlist]</ref>\n\nCallaghan's full album \"Life in Full Colour\" was completed in 2011 and initially made available as pre-release Limited Edition copies to fans through her website<ref>[http://www.callaghansongs.com Callaghan Artist Website]</ref> and at live shows.\n\nThe album released in 2012 to great reviews:\n\n<blockquote>\n\"A 12-track set infused with folk, pop, rock and country influences and, above all, immediate hooks\" \n\u2013 '''Billboard.com'''\n</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>\n\"Life In Full Colour by Callaghan proves that this Brit has been listening to her Joni Mitchell, Bonnie Raitt and Sheryl Crow records. ...Girl can write. Girl can sing. Girl can play piano. Girl has captured my heart. Callaghan, oh Callaghan, sing me back home\"\n\u2013 '''Aquarian Weekly'''\n</blockquote>\n\n<blockquote>\n\"The world needs more singer songwriters like Callaghan. In a time where mediocrity is seen as brilliant, Callaghan truly shines through as the real deal. Her voice is original and pure, and she is one of the greatest unsigned talents I've ever heard.\"\n\u2013 '''Shawn Mullins'''<ref>Shawn Mullins News 6 July 2009 | retrieved from [http://www.shawnmullins.com/news.html on 29 May 2012] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414102814/http://www.shawnmullins.com/news.html |date=14 April 2012 }}</ref> \n</blockquote>\nAfter living in [[Atlanta]] for a few years she moved to [[Nashville]] in 2012 after completing 4 tours opening for Mullins.\nIn June 2013 [[Billboard Magazine]] published a four-page article titled ''House Music'' which detailed her first show in [[Boston]] as part of her ''Callaghan Across America Tour'' describing the exposure that [[house concert]]s can provide for both independent and established artists.<ref name=\"Billboard Magazine\">[http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/1567029/house-music-your-living-room-might-be-your-next-concert-venue / House Music: Your Living Room Might Be Your Next Concert Venue by Gary Trust] Retrieved on 2013-11-17, published 14 June 2013</ref>\nOn 22 September 2013 [[BBC Radio 2]] broadcast a recorded live session with Callaghan for the [[Bob Harris (radio)|Bob Harris]] Sunday show as part of his week in Nashville covering the [[Americana Music Honors & Awards|Americana Awards]]. \n<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p01h41jn   Bob Harris Sunday BBC Radio 2 playlist/] Retrieved 2013-11-17, published 22 September 2013</ref>\n\n== Influences ==\nCallaghan's music is a blend of pop/rock/singer-songwriter genres, with influences from great artists including Shawn Mullins, Sarah McLachlan, [[Johnny Cash]] and [[James Taylor]]. \nHer voice has been compared to artists including [[Sarah McLachlan]] and [[Alison Krauss]].\n\n== Discography ==\n\n'''Albums'''\n*[[Life In Full Colour (Callaghan album)|''Life in Full Colour'']] (2012)\n*''Callaghan: Live in America'' (2013)\n*''A History of Now'' (2015)\n*''Callaghan'' (2018)\n\n'''EPs'''\n*''Callaghan'' (2005)\n*''Road To Elmersville'' (2006)\n*''Nothing You Say'' (2007)\n*''The Other Side'' (2017)\n*''Skin on Skin'' (2018)\n\n'''Singles'''\n*''Look Around'' (2008)\n*''Smile'' (2009)\n*''Surrender (Acoustic)'' (2017)\n*''I Don't Know How To Lose You (Acoustic)'' (2017)\n\n== Collaborations ==\n*Album \"Life in Full Colour\" produced by [[Shawn Mullins]]\n* \"Sweet Surrender\" (Life in Full Colour) co-written by Callaghan and [[Shawn Mullins]]\n* \"The Only Thing Real\" (Life in Full Colour) co-written by Callaghan and [[Shawn Mullins]]\n*EP \"London To Lawrenceville\" 3 songs produced by [[Shawn Mullins]]\n\n==Quotes==\n*  \"Having seen her do a showcase earlier this year, I thought she was wonderful\" \u2013 Bob Harris OBE (BBC Radio 2)<ref>Callaghan: played on Bob Harris Saturday Show, BBC Radio 2: 2 January 2010: retrieved from http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00pk7w4 on 3 January 2010</ref>\n* \"One of the best albums of last year, LIFE IN FULL COLOUR, for Callaghan\" \u2013 Bob Harris OBE (BBC Radio 2).<ref>Bob Harris Sunday,BBC Radio 2: 8 January 2012: retrieved from http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01932rv on 9 January 2012</ref>\n*  \"A 12-track set infused with folk, pop, rock and country influences and, above all, immediate hooks\" \u2013 Billboard<ref>Billboard Story: Chart Beat Meet & Greet: Callaghan by Gary Trust: 1 May 2012 retrieved from\nhttp://www.billboard.com/articles/chartbeat/46391/chart-beat-meet-greet-callaghan-exclusive-video</ref>\n\n* \"Life In Full Colour is joyful listening\" \u2013 Huffington Post<ref>Performing Songwriter Callaghan Releases Life in Full Colour, article/interview by Ruth Gerson: 8 May 2012 retrieved from http://www.huffingtonpost.com/ruth-gerson/performing-songwriter-callaghan_b_1484833.html</ref>\n{{commonscat}}\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|id=5746409|name=Callaghan}}\n*[http://www.callaghansongs.com Callaghan's Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Callaghan, Georgina}}\n[[Category:British singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Kesteven and Grantham Girls' School]]\n[[Category:People from Boston, Lincolnshire]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century British singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2009}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image               = Callaghan 5 24 2014 -10 (14270528514).jpg\n| name                = Georgina Callaghan\n| caption             = \n| image_size          =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_date          = \n| origin              = [Grantham, Lincolnshire], England\n| instrument          = singing, acoustic guitar, piano\n| genre               = Pop singer-songwriter\n| occupation          = Singer-songwriter\n| years_active        = 2005\u2013present\n| label               = Green Town Music\n| associated_acts = [[Shawn Mullins]]\n| website             = {{url|https://callaghansongs.com}}\n}}\n\nBritish artist Callaghan (full name Georgina Callaghan) is a singer-songwriter. She performs under the name Callaghan. She is best known for her 2012 album \"Life in Full Colour\" produced by Grammy-nominated US artist Shawn Mullins.\n\nCallaghan is currently living in Los Angeles where she is recording her 3rd studio album.\n\n== Biography ==\nCallaghan wrote her first song at the age of 14 and earned a place on [[BBC]] TV show ''Get Your Act Together'',<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0187641   The Internet Movie Database Page]</ref> hosted by Irish singer [[Ronan Keating]].\n\nCallaghan has worked with many musicians and producers including Grammy Award-winning writer John Peppard (1998, [[Grammy Award for Best Country Collaboration with Vocals|Best Country Collaboration with Vocals]] for \"[[In Another's Eyes]]\") and producer Peter Lawlor who formed the band [[Stiltskin]].<ref>[http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=Garth+Brooks&title=&year=1997&genre=8   1998 Grammy Award Database]</ref><ref>[http://www.amug.org/~scrnsrc/grammys_98.html Screen Source presents The 40th Annual Grammy Awards| Screen Source presents The 40th Annual Grammy Awards] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017114952/http://www.amug.org/~scrnsrc/grammys_98.html |date=17 October 2007 }}</ref> \n[[Image:Callaghannationaltheatre.JPG|thumb|320px|left|Callaghan performing at The National Theatre London 2009]]\n\nIn 2008, Callaghan self-released single \"Look Around\". Doing all of the PR and radio plugging herself, Callaghan achieved airplay on numerous [[BBC]] radio stations, extensive local and national press coverage as well as a performance on [[British Sky Broadcasting|Sky TV]].<ref>[http://www.metro.co.uk/fame/article.html?Georgina_Callaghan_takes_on_X_Factor&in_article_id=355894&in_page_id=7 Metro.co.uk]</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=48im-bdo1aI Callaghan performs Look Around on Sky TV]</ref> All proceeds from the sale of the single went to music charity Live Music Now.<ref>[http://www.prsformusic.com/creators/news/news/Pages/Callaghan.aspx PRS Web site]</ref>\n\nIn July 2009, Callaghan travelled to [[Georgia, USA]] to record with US artist [[Shawn Mullins]]. The first single from the collaboration \"Smile\" was played and endorsed on the [[Bob Harris (radio)|Bob Harris]] Country Show on [[BBC Radio 2]].<ref>[http://www.bobharris.org/pages/playlist.asp?progcode=c13082009 Bob Harris Country Show Playlist]</ref>\n\nCallaghan's full album \"Life in Full Colour\" was completed in 2011 and initially made available as pre-release Limited Edition copies to fans through her website<ref>[http://www.callaghansongs.